bility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.95,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hydrothermal reductive amination path is experimentally demonstrated (Kaur et al. 2024). Transformation of pyruvate to alpha-ketoisovalerate (rxn_007, transamination) and subsequent conversion by H2 and Ni to valine is robustly justified. The environmental mapping (hydrothermal vent analogs, Ni mineral catalysis) is excellent and matches literature. The downgrade of rxn_004 reflects that the hydrolysis step is not engaged directly in this path (product comes from rxn_006).\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify possible sources of pyruvate and the mechanistic logic for transamination or highlight possible Ni/FeS surfaces as catalysts.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 1.0\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid surface-to-hydrothermal route is plausible: it tracks formaldehyde through glycolaldehyde to pyruvate (well-documented, FeS-catalyzed), then to alpha-ketoisovalerate and reductive amination to valine. The depiction of environmental transition is strong. Some uncertainty exists for efficiency of C\u2013C bond formation at the glycolaldehyde/pyruvate stages (which are best for straight-chain products, less so for branched), but such steps are not unreasonable.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Cite literature showing glycolaldehyde/aldol reactions yielding branched intermediates, or note any yield caveats.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"The direct spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) route is supported by experiments, but yields are very low and the product is a complex mixture. Synthesis of valine is possible (Johnson et al. 2009 confirmed), but not selective; other amino acids dominate. The pathway, while real, is inefficient prebiotically.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note that the route is non-selective and inefficient as a primary source; mainly serves as proof-of-principle or for meteoritic delivery.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_003\": 1.0,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid integration of cyanosulfidic and Strecker steps is creative and reflects recent network models. It is plausible, with each step individually supported by literature. Environment flow is well mapped, and route redundancy (multiple intermediates to hub molecules) is a strength. Only minor detail is that several sequential surface transformations may have limited yields.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Address the likelihood of yield depletion due to side reactions at each step or specify purification mechanisms if available.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_006\": 1.0\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.9,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route is a succinct sequence from acetone/glycolaldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate, then to valine by hydrothermal Ni-catalyzed hydrogenation. The steps are justified (aldol to alpha-ketoisovalerate, then hydrogenation), but as with P4, the availability of branched intermediates depends on aldehyde/ketone selectivity.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"State any known selectivity issues in the surface aldol step or highlight possible mineral selectivity enhancement.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 1.0\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"Another hybrid surface\u2013hydrothermal path. Good environmental justification for each transition and strong literature support for all reaction types. Main limitation is as above: feasibility of selective formation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from these precursors in prebiotic conditions.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_003\": 1.0,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"Stapled pathway combining cyanosulfidic and Strecker mechanisms. This strengthens redundancy and increases likelihood of successful valine formation in variable environments.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 1.0\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"Replicates P8 with a full Fe-Ni-catalyzed conversion chain. All steps known experimentally. Topology supports convergence from simple C1 feedstocks through branched intermediates.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": []\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.96,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This synthesis network for valine is exceptionally comprehensive and directly aligns with all major experimentally verified prebiotic synthesis routes (Strecker, cyanosulfidic, reductive amination, and spark-discharge). Major hub nodes (e.g., isobutyraldehyde, acetone, alpha-ketoisovalerate, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde) are all correctly identified and are multi-connected, supporting a robust and convergent topology. Pathways span all  environmental stages; environmental flows (hydrothermal \u2194 surface \u2192 biochemical) are explicit and well justified both mechanistically and by referenced literature. Each pathway shows rigorous chemical plausibility, and the reaction types, intermediates, and mineral/photochemical agents correspond closely to the state of the art described in the cited studies. Limitations mainly concern realistic yields and competitive side reactions in less selective steps (especially for the direct spark route and some radical or aldol condensation pathways). However, the redundancy and interconnection across the network substantially mitigate these issues. All steps, intermediates, and outcomes are grounded in experimental precedent. Literature alignment is outstanding, with all proposed steps and environmental transitions supported, addressing known challenges (e.g., precursor formation, need for mineral catalysis, environmental setting realism). Overall, this network is a model standard for prebiotic amino acid network design.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 1.0,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.98\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.95, "rxn_003": 1.0, "rxn_004": 0.95}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.97, "pathway_coherence": 0.98, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 1.0, "overall_confidence": 0.97, "feedback": "This is the canonical Strecker synthesis route for valine: well-supported by decades of literature. The sequence\u2014aldol condensation to make isobutyraldehyde, Strecker synthesis with NH3 and HCN to valine aminonitrile, and hydrolysis to valine\u2014represents experimentally validated steps (see Miller & Schlesinger 1993, Powner et al. 2019). Usage of surface then biochemical environments is realistic. The only slight limitation is the source/abundance of isobutyraldehyde in prebiotic settings; the network addresses this by making it from acetone and formaldehyde (rxn_002).", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Include mention of possible mineral catalysis for the Strecker step (e.g., Zn/Ca/Fe minerals) for extra realism."]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_005": 0.95, "rxn_004": 0.95}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.93, "pathway_coherence": 0.92, "environmental_progression": 0.95, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.93, "feedback": "The cyanosulfidic photochemical route is directly suppo